{
 "title": "A serialized cert-and-listing critical path zeroes H1 revenue — 'conservative ramp' is not linear in months",
 "narrative": "The YAM implicitly assumes the selling machine exists on day 1 of the 12-month window. But an intelligent PDU sold into CE must first clear a compliance stack the model only gestures at: CE (LVD/EMC), RoHS, WEEE producer registration (Germany's stiftung EAR is a named, dated gate), EORI customs registration, and the buyer-side pull-through of EU 2024/1364 (DC rating scheme, in force May 2024) and EED 2024/1791 KPI disclosures that operators now push down into vendor questionnaires. These gates are serialized — test slots before declaration, registration before listing, listing before quote. A two-quarter slip does not scale YAM by 50% linearly; it deletes the ramp's compounding front end, because the conservative ramp back-loads revenue into quarters that no longer exist.",
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "The real EU entry stack is materially larger than the three regimes the ledger cites: WEEE, ROHS, FCC, EORI customs, plus the 2024 DC rating scheme and EED disclosure duties landing on operators and flowing into vendor requirements",
   "refs": [
    "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c10",
    "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c8",
